essity of moral, social, political, and economic equality. These essays on the black experience in America range from sociological studies of the African American community to illuminating discourses on religion and “Negro music,” and remain essential reading in our so-called “post-racial age.” A new introduction by Jonathan Scott Holloway explores Du Bois’s signature accomplishments while helping readers to better understand his writings in the context of his time as well as ours.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican AmericansxHistory. 0aAfrican AmericansxIntellectual life. 0aAfrican AmericansxSocial conditions. 0aAfrican AmericansxStudy and teaching (Higher). 0aAfrican Americans. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh1 aHolloway, Jonathan Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106725030 cprintz978030019582840uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030021372040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300213720423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300213720/original  a978-3-11-067250-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY